Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship
left to right direction

actor "Customer" as Customer
actor "Restaurant" as Restaurant
actor "Delivery Driver" as Driver

rectangle "Food Delivery Platform" {
  usecase "Browse Restaurants" as UC1
  usecase "Place Order" as UC2
  usecase "Track Delivery" as UC3
  usecase "Update Menu" as UC4
  usecase "Validate Delivery Address" as UC5
  usecase "Accept Delivery" as UC6
}

Customer -- UC1
Customer -- UC2
Customer -- UC3
Restaurant -- UC4
Driver -- UC6

UC2 ..> UC5 : <<include>>
@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Place Order (UC2), Validate Delivery Address (UC5), the <<include>> relationship from UC2 to UC5
   Explanation: "Validate Delivery Address" (UC5) is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Place Order" / UC2). It is not associated with any actor directly. It does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any use case, and is not involved in any generalization. "Validate Delivery Address" represents a sub-step of placing an order rather than a complete, independently valuable service observable to an actor. This is a textbook instance of Functional Decomposition via the include relationship — the designer has decomposed the "Place Order" behavior into a separate inclusion use case that has no standalone value.
